article.description: Rasheed Wallace and Derek Anderson combined for seven 3-pointers and 41 points to lead the Portland Trail Blazers to a 92-77 victory over the SuperSonics and a sweep of the season series.
article.headline: Blazers wrap up season sweep of Sonics
article.linkText: Blazers, Anderson wrap up season sweep of Sonics
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Derek Anderson did it with his shooting when the Portland Trail Blazers needed it in the third quarter. As for his defense on Ray Allen, he did it all night.
Anderson

Anderson scored 13 of his 18 points in the third period as the Portland Trail Blazers beat the Seattle SuperSonics 92-77 on Tuesday night, completing a season sweep of their Northwest rival. Anderson and Portland held Allen to 14 points on 6-of-18 shooting, snapping his streak of eight straight games with at least 20 points. "We didn't wait on them to make a move,'' Anderson said. "I tried to make Ray dribble more and come off screens. We just tried to pressure them and take them out of their rhythm.'' Allen never could establish a groove. He missed four of his first five shots and was 4-of-11 going into the fourth quarter. "They just kept bothering me all night,'' Allen said. "The looks I had, because I wanted it so bad, I started to press it. Tonight was a combination of no shots and them staying on us all night.'' Anderson shot 4-of-6 in the third period, including all three of his 3-pointers. He had one on a kickout from Arvydas Sabonis, capping a 21-7 run for a 69-59 lead going into the fourth quarter. "That's a team that doubles everybody,'' Anderson said. "They double from every position. There's only so many times you can get around the arc. You just have to take advantage.'' Rasheed Wallace scored 23 points and reserve Zach Randolph scored nine of his 17 points in the fourth quarter. Scottie Pippen added 10 points and 13 rebounds and pestered the Seattle ballhandlers, helping to force 18 turnovers. "Scottie's 6-foot-8, so he can cover a lot of ground,'' Blazers coach Maurice Cheeks said. "His wingspan helps us disrupt guys going up the floor and he can also disrupt guys trying to post the ball.'' The Trail Blazers won without their second-leading scorer, Bonzi Wells, who was suspended for one game after an undisclosed episode at the team's practice Monday. He wasn't missed. Kevin Ollie had a season-high 15 points and tied his career-high with 11 assists, while Vladimir Radmanovic had 14 and Brent Barry scored 10. Seattle shot 41 percent and was outrebounded 41-27 in losing its third straight. "We have to double-team to match up with their post players. When you do that, you sometimes leave yourselves vulnerable to weak-side rebounding,'' Sonics coach Nate McMillan said. The Sonics had erased a 12-point deficit in the first half, and they seemed ready to charge again when Rashard Lewis and Allen opened the final period with jumpers to force a Portland timeout. Elden Campbell made a nice spin move around Wallace and scored to get Seattle within 71-65 with 10:10 to play, but that was as close as things got. After Randolph scored on a putback, Campbell fouled Wallace on a successful 3-pointer and Wallace made the foul shot for a four-point play and a 75-65 lead. Dale Davis added another basket, forcing a Seattle timeout with 6:24 to go. "There are nights when things just don't work out for you,'' Barry said. "Our locker room just needs to stay positive and keep building.''

Game notes
Pippen hit a 10-footer midway through the first period, passing Bob McAdoo (18,787) for 41st place on the NBA's career scoring list. ... Reserves Radmanovic and Ollie combined for 24 points on 9-of-12 shooting in the first half for the Sonics. ... Ruben Patterson, who strained his right groin against Indiana last weekend, started in place of Wells. He scored 11 points in 31 minutes. ... Lewis had nine points, ending his streak of 28 games scoring in double figures.
